# saneland — local Hyprland overrides
#
# Sourced from hyprland.conf (end of its Variables section), AFTER the base
# defaults and BEFORE the keybinds — so anything set here wins and is visible
# to the keybinds. This file is git-ignored: your machine-specific settings
# live here while the tracked base config stays identical for everyone.
# install.sh copies this to ~/.config/hypr/local.conf on first run; edit that
# real file (not the .example).

# --- Monitors --------------------------------------------------------------
# You usually DON'T need anything here. The base config's
# `monitor = , preferred, auto, 1` wildcard auto-detects any new output at its
# native mode and places it to the right — plug a monitor in and it just works.
# Add a line below ONLY for a monitor with a quirk the wildcard gets wrong
# (wrong refresh rate, wrong scale, a specific arrangement you want).
#
#   monitor = MATCH, RESOLUTION@REFRESH, POSITION, SCALE
#
# MATCH BY `desc:`, NOT BY CONNECTOR NAME. A connector like DP-2 is just a
# physical port: unplug the TV, plug in a different monitor, and it lands on
# the SAME DP-2 — inheriting the TV's line and, say, being forced into a 4K
# mode it can't display (blank screen). `desc:` matches the actual monitor by
# its EDID, so the rule only ever touches the monitor it was written for, and
# anything else falls through to the auto wildcard. Find the string with
# `hyprctl monitors | grep description` (drop the trailing serial for a rule
# that matches any unit of that model):
# monitor = eDP-1, 2256x1504@60, 0x0, 1.5666667                 # laptop panel (by connector is fine — it's soldered in)
# monitor = desc:Dell Inc. DELL U2312HM, 1920x1080@60, 1440x0, 1 # a specific external
#
# `hyprctl monitors all | grep availableModes` shows every mode an output
# supports.
#
# Fractional-scale tip: use Hyprland's *exact* suggested scale from
# `hyprctl monitors`, not a rounded value — a fresh session rejects e.g. 1.5
# with "Invalid scale passed to monitor".
#
# POSITION is in LOGICAL pixels, not physical ones. To place a second output
# flush to the right of the panel above, its x is the panel's logical width —
# 2256 / 1.5666667 = 1440 — NOT its physical 2256. Get this wrong and you
# either leave a dead gap the cursor crosses invisibly, or overlap the two.
#
# PIN THE REFRESH RATE for displays that advertise a slow preferred mode. Many
# 4K TVs report 3840x2160@30 as preferred even though the link does @60 fine,
# so the wildcard runs them at 30Hz — a laggy cursor and stuttery scrolling
# rather than an obvious error. Check availableModes and state @60 explicitly.

# --- App choices -----------------------------------------------------------
